title_full:
Byard Lancaster

              —
              It’s Not Up To Us
            
              (Superior Viaduct)
label: Superior Viaduct
description:
Generously spirited jazz classic from the pivotal year of 1968, including a killer take on ‘Over the Rainbow’ and the mesmerising ‘Satan’, reissued for the first time since its maiden voyage on Atlantic’s Vortex - a springboard for important debuts by Sonny Shamrock, Chick Corea, Keith Jarrett

title_full:
Tongue in the Mind

              —
              Pretty Canary
            
              (PAN)
label: PAN
description:
Juliana Huxtable, Via App and Joe Rinaldo Heffernan light the touch-paper with their blindingly bizarre debut single, charismatically mutilating prog rock, b-movie electronix, symphonic punk and pinched electro in the process. A firework display for anyone into Siouxsie and the Banshees, Drexciya, Yeah Yeah Yeahs, Kathy Acker or Lizzy Mercier Descloux.

It would have been far too obvious for Huxtable to emerge with a project that simply built on her reputation as a DJ. She's been developing... more

description:
Blonde Redhead's Sit Down for Dinner, their debut for section1. 

"It's title a nod to the often-sacred communal ritual of sharing a meal with those you love, this immersive, meticulously crafted album appropriately serves an expression of persistent togetherness, a testament to the unique internal logic Blonde Redhead have refined over their three-decade existence.

title_full:
Rainy Miller & Space Afrika

              —
              A Grisaille Wedding
            
              (Fixed Abode)
label: Fixed Abode
description:
Space Afrika and Rainy Miller mesh traces of burnt trip-hop, concrète ambience and industrialised drill on their debut collaborative full-length, offering an idiosyncratic, historically seasoned silhouette of the urban sprawl. Featuring Voice Actor, Mica Levi, Iceboy Violet, Coby Sey, Richie Culver, RenzNiro and bobbieorkid.

Preston's Rainy Miller and Manchester-Berlin duo Space Afrika have long circled each other, so it was inevitable that their sounds would collide at some point. And they took the... more

title_full:
Charles M. Bogert

              —
              Sounds of North American Frogs
            
              (Smithsonian Folkways)
label: Smithsonian Folkways
description:
One of the most enduring releases on the Folkways label, 'Sounds of North American Frogs' was originally released in 1958, and collects sounds from 57 species of frogs and toads, each couched by Charles M. Bogert's soothing narrative. Remastered from the original tapes, it's an absolute delight that's finally been reissues for the first time in almost 7 decades.

On 'Sounds of North American Frogs', herpetologist Charles M. Bogert demystifies his particular frog chorus by introducing each... more

title_full:
Ahl Nana

              —
              L’Orchestre National Mauritanien
            
              (Radio Martiko)
label: Radio Martiko
description:
Unmissable first reissue of desert blues’ astonishing ground zero - the first recording of electric guitars in Saharan folk, paving the way for Ali Farka Touré, Tinariwen, Mdou Moctar and Bombino. 

100% essential for anyone enchanted by the heat-hazy sway of what has become known as desert blues, the gorgeous family affair of L’Orchestra National Mauritanien changed the course of Western Saharan music in 1971 via their seamless incorporation of electric guitar to traditional folk... more
